{"title_page": "John Max", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = John Max\n| honorific_suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|RCA}}\n| birth_name       = John Porchawka\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|year=1936|month=September|day=23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Montr\u00e9al]], [[Canada]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2011|05|05|1936|09|23|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Montr\u00e9al]], [[Canada]]\n| nationality      = Canadian\n| education        = School of Art and Design, [[Mus\u00e9e des beaux-arts de Montr\u00e9al]]\n| known_for        = Photography, film\n| notable_works    = ''Le soleil brilla toute la nuit'' (1970)<br />''...to be INDIAN'' (1971)<br />''Open Passport'' (1972)\n| style            = Portrait, sequence\n| awards           = {{awd|Dipl\u00f4me d\u2019honneur and M\u00e9daille de bronze de la ville de [[Bordeaux]] |(1972)|||}}\n{{awd|[[National Film Board of Canada]] Gold Medal for Excellence in Photography|(1972)|||}}\n| elected          = [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]] (1974)\n}}\n\n'''John Max''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|RCA}} (born '''John Porchawka'''; 23 September 1936 \u2013 5 May 2011) was a Canadian photojournalist, photography teacher, and art photographer. He is recognized for his use of the narrative sequence, his expressive portraiture, and his intensely personal, subjective approach to photography.\n\nHe grew up in [[Montr\u00e9al]], where he participated in the visual arts scene of the city during the late 1950s and early 1960s, and published numerous photo-essays for newspapers and magazines. He also maintained close ties to the American photography scene.\n\nMax was championed during the 1960s and 1970s by the [[National Film Board of Canada]], through its [[National Film Board of Canada#Still Photography Division|Still Photography Division]], and the [[National Gallery of Canada]], through a variety of exhibition and publication projects. Gradually abandoning photojournalism during the 1960s, he focused his work on photographic art exhibitions and publications. His best-known work, ''Open Passport'' (exhibited 1972\u20131976; published 1973) is a long sequence that combined photographs from diverse sources shot over the span of a decade into a unified, poetical narrative.\n\nFollowing a long trip to [[Japan]] (1974\u20131978) that resulted in his deportation and the loss of many rolls of films, he became less visible than before on the arts scene in Canada. During the late 1990s and early 2000s, he benefitted from a regain of interest in his work, before his death in 2011.\n\nThe work of John Max has been recognized by a number of critics, curators, artists, and photographers in Canada and abroad. It has also been the source of a number of responses and homages. [[Robert Frank]] said about him \"When I think of Canadian photography, his name comes up first.\"<ref name=\"Manford\">{{cite journal |last1=Manford |first1=Steven |title=Of Passports and Visas |journal=[[Canadian Art (magazine)|Canadian Art]] |date=1997 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=56 |url=https://canadianart.ca/issues/fall-1997/ |issn=08253854}}</ref>\n== Early years ==\n\nJohn Max was born John Porchawka to the family of Anna (n\u00e9e Barchynska) and Paul Porchawka, both immigrants of [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] origins, on 23 September 1936 in Montr\u00e9al.<ref name=\"NGC-Max\">{{cite web |title=John Max |url=https://www.gallery.ca/collection/artist/john-max |website=[[National Gallery of Canada]]}}</ref> His family lived in the multicultural area around [[The Main]], until they moved to the [[Rosemont\u2013La Petite-Patrie|Rosemont]] neighbourhood, where Max spent the greater part of his life.<ref name=\"Block\">{{cite news |last1=Block |first1=Irwin |title=Photographer finds a home |url=https://montrealgazette.newspapers.com/image/425515179/ |work=[[Montreal Gazette|The Gazette]] |date=24 April 2003}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref>\n\nDuring high school, he attended the [[Montr\u00e9al Museum of Fine Arts]] School of Arts and Design. Headed by [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] painter [[Arthur Lismer]], the School offered both adult and children classes taught by career artists on a variety of media, such as textile, painting, typography, graphic arts, drawing, or design.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Grigor |first1=Angela |title=Arthur Lismer, Visionary Art Educator |date=2002 |publisher=[[McGill-Queen's University Press]] |location=Montr\u00e9al and Kingston |isbn=9780773522954 |page=176 |url=https://www.mqup.ca/arthur-lismer--visionary-art-educator-products-9780773522954.php}}</ref> Porchawka distinguished himself and won scholarships for his standing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prizes, Scholarships Given At School of Art and Design |url=https://montrealgazette.newspapers.com/image/419591639/ |work=The Gazette |date=7 April 1952 |page=13}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref> He had also started taking photographs with a [[Kodak Pony 135]].<ref name=\"FotoCanada\">{{cite journal |last1=Tata |first1=Sam |author-link1=Sam Tata|title=On assignment: John Max by Sam Tata |journal=Foto-Canada |volume=I |issue=3 |date=1968 |pages=29\u201335 |oclc=173996291}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduating from high school, Porchawka studied at the [[McGill Conservatory]] but quickly abandoned his studies and focused instead on photography.<ref name=\"FotoCanada\" /> He cited the work of [[Henri Cartier-Bresson]] and [[Lutz Dille]] in [[photojournalism]] and [[street photography]] as early models. Through his frequentation of the Montr\u00e9al [[Bohemianism|bohemia]] in caf\u00e9s such as L\u2019\u00c9chourie,<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =  [[Jean Palardy|Palardy, Jean]] (Director)\n | date = 1954\n | title = Artist in Montreal\n | medium = 16 mm\n | url = https://www.onf.ca/film/artist_in_montreal/\n | time = 11:29\n | publisher = [[National Film Board of Canada]]\n | oclc = 1078057077\n}}</ref> he became acquainted with a number of artistic figures in the field of painting, sculpture, writing, theatre, cinema, and photography.<ref name=\"FotoCanada\" /><ref name=\"JCG_FN\">{{cite book |last1=Germain |first1=Jean-Claude |author-link1=Jean-Claude Germain |title=La femme nue habillait la nuit : Nouvelles historiettes de la boh\u00e8me |language=French |date=2010 |publisher=Hurtubise |location=Montr\u00e9al |isbn=9782896473144 |url=https://editionshurtubise.com/livre/la-femme-nue-habillait-la-nuit/}}</ref> For many years he photographed Montr\u00e9al artists intensively, hoping to produce a \u201cportrait of the bohemia.\u201d<ref name=\"JCG_FN\" /> This general direction yielded material for his first exhibitions and publications under the name \u201cJohn Max.\u201d Max\u2019s magazine output slowed down during the second half of the 1960s, and his practice took a turn primarily toward art photography for the rest of his career.\n\n=== 1957\u20131965: Montr\u00e9al bohemia ===\n\nIn 1957, John Max contributed a short photographic sequence and a portrait to the group exhibition ''Photographie 57'' at [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]].<ref name=\"Photo57\">{{cite book |last1=Millet |first1=Robert |title=quelques uns des travaux expos\u00e9s d\u2019abord \u00e0 l\u2019Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al en f\u00e9vrier \u201957 par un groupe qui croit que la photographie est autre chose qu\u2019un m\u00e9dium impersonnel de reproduction\u2026 |date=1957 |language=French |oclc=938043393 |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Artistique de l\u2019Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al |location=Montr\u00e9al}}</ref> It was an anticipated response to the visit of the [[MoMA]] exhibition ''[[The Family of Man]]'' later that year at the [[Montreal Museum of Fine Arts]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hone |first1=Marie-Sol |title=Exposition de photographies |journal=Quartier Latin |date=21 February 1957 |page=5 |language=French |issn=0832-4131}}</ref> Championing photography as an art form, the exhibition counted among its participants [[Claude Jutra]], [[Michel Brault]], John Max, [[Vittorio Fiorucci]], Jauran ([[Rodolphe de Repentigny]]), [[Jean-Paul Mousseau]], Gordon Webber, and many others.<ref name=\"Photo57\" /> Around the same time,  Max reached out to the [[George Eastman House]] with the help of [[Sam Tata]] and [[Vittorio Fiorucci]]. He met [[Nathan Lyons]], who supported him throughout his career and included him in the GEH exhibition ''Photography 63.''<ref name=\"NGC-report\">{{cite book |title=Touching Canadians: Annual Report 2002\u20132003 |publisher=National Gallery of Canada |location=Ottawa |page=30 |url=https://www.gallery.ca/sites/default/files/documents/planning%20and%20reporting/02-03annual_e.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Confino\">{{cite news |last1=Confino |first1=Barbara |title=Intimate Images |work=[[The Montreal Star]] |date=7 October 1972 |page=C5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Photography 63 / An International Exhibition |date=1963 |publisher=George Eastman House |location=Rochester, NY |oclc=613432467}}</ref>\n\nJohn Max\u2019s first solo exhibition opened in 1960 at [[McGill University]], but it was promptly censored and shut down: ''John Max Shouts: Enough, No More, I Want'' was relocated to a private club nearby.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sarrazin |first1=Jean |title=Des jeunes de mille ans et des jeunes d\u2019aujourd\u2019hui\u2026 |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2755656?docpos=36 |work=[[La Presse (Canadian newspaper)|La Presse]] |date=5 March 1960 |language=French |page=36}}</ref> It featured, among other sequences, a performance of modernist dancer [[Suzanne Rivest]] cast as stations of the cross, a suggestion of Max\u2019s friend [[Jean-Claude Germain]].<ref name=\"JCG_FN\" />\n\nMax had become by then a regular contributor to magazines and newspaper supplements, providing photo-essays about the Montr\u00e9al artistic scene for ''[[Maclean\u2019s]]'', ''Perspectives'', ''{{ill|Vie des arts|fr}}'', and ''Weekend Magazine'', photographing among others [[Jacques Hurtubise (painter)|Jacques Hurtubise]], [[Rita Letendre]], Laure Major, Marcella Maltais, [[Suzanne Meloche]], [[Robert Roussil]] and [[Armand Vaillancourt]]. His portrait of poet [[Leonard Cohen]] also adorned the cover of the first edition of ''[[The Spice-Box of Earth]]'' (1961). Most notably, he contributed to ''Maclean\u2019s'' a reportage on the Montr\u00e9al artistic scene, \u201cThe Last Bohemia,\u201d<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Max |first1=John |title=The Last Bohemia |journal=[[Maclean's]] |date=22 April 1961 |pages=24\u201327 |url=https://archive.macleans.ca/issue/19610422#!&pid=24}}</ref> and another about the [[Cree]] [[Mistissini, Quebec|community]] of [[Lake Mistassini]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Max |first1=John |title=Some Indians with no White Problem \u2014 Yet |journal=Maclean's |date=6 July 1963 |pages=22\u201324}}</ref> The latter helped establish his reputation<ref>{{cite web |title=1964 Editorial Art, Picture Story |url=http://archive.theadcc.ca/islandora/object/adcc%3A52550 |website=Advertising & Design Club of Canada}}</ref> and draw the attention of [[Lorraine Monk]], executive producer of the [[National Film Board of Canada#Still Photography Division|Still Photography Division]] of the [[National Film Board of Canada]].\n\n=== 1966\u20131970: Institutional recognition and underground ===\n\nThe [[National Film Board of Canada#Still Photography Division|SPD]] acquired some of Max\u2019s photographs from [[Mistissini, Quebec|Mistassini (today Mistissini, Quebec)]] in 1965,<ref>{{cite web |title=Mistassini, John Max |url=https://www.gallery.ca/collection/search-the-collection?search_api_views_fulltext=john+max+mistassini&sort_by=search_api_relevance&f%5B0%5D=field_reference_artist%253Atitle%3AJohn+Max&f%5B1%5D=field_date_made_earliest_year%3A%5B1960+TO+1979%5D |website=National Gallery of Canada}}</ref> and he did a number of assignments for the Division over the following years. This got him included in a series of NFB publications, starting with the [[Canadian Centennial]] books ''Call Them Canadians'' and ''Ces visages qui sont un pays'' (1968),<ref>{{cite book |editor-last1=Monk |editor-first1=Lorraine |editor-link1=Lorraine Monk |title=Call them Canadians: A Photographic Point of View |date=1968 |publisher=Queen\u2019s Printer |location=Ottawa |oclc=622822727}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor-last1=Monk |editor-first1=Lorraine |title=Ces visages qui sont un pays |date=1968 |language=French |publisher=Imprimeur de la Reine |location=Ottawa |oclc=604354983}}</ref> as well as exhibition catalogues in the IMAGE series (1967\u20131970).<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Monk |editor1-first=Lorraine\n|title=Photography = Photographie Canada 1967\n|date=1968\n|publisher=National Film Board of Canada\n|location=Ottawa\n|oclc=191407\n|series=IMAGE vol. 2 |language=English,French\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Monk |editor1-first=Lorraine\n|title=Other Places = Sous d\u2019autres cieux\n|date=1968\n|publisher=National Film Board of Canada\n|location=Ottawa\n|oclc= 30071341\n|series=IMAGE vol. 3 |language=English,French\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Monk |editor1-first=Lorraine\n|title=Seeds of the spacefields (a sequence of ten dreams) = cela commen\u00e7a par un r\u00eave et ce fut la Cr\u00e9ation (une s\u00e9rie de dix r\u00eaves)\n|date=1969\n|publisher=Martlet Press\n|location=Toronto\n|oclc=62931108\n|series=IMAGE vol. 5 |language=English,French\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Monk |editor1-first=Lorraine\n|title=Image 6: A Review of Contemporary Photography in Canada = Une revue de la photographie contemporaine au Canada\n|date=1970\n|publisher=Martlet Press\n|location=Toronto\n|oclc=1131342409\n|series=IMAGE vol. 6 |language=English,French\n}}</ref> The National Gallery of Canada also supported him, and he was chosen in 1967 to represent Canada at the [[Biennale de Paris|5<sup>e</sup> Biennale de Paris]], alongside sculptor [[Henry Saxe]], engraver Pierre H\u00e9bert, and filmmaker [[Al Sens]]. Max presented a sequence of six photographs on the imposed theme of the fantastic, for which he was awarded a [[French franc|1000 F]] prize.<ref>{{cite book |title=Cinqui\u00e8me biennale de Paris |publisher=[[Mus\u00e9e d'Art Moderne de Paris|Mus\u00e9e d\u2019art moderne de Paris]] |location=Paris |language=French |oclc=983760774 |page=46}}</ref>\n\nHe was included in numerous group exhibitions in Canada, traveled to [[England]] and [[France]], and was appointed as a teacher in photography at [[Loyola College (Montreal)|Loyola College]] in Montr\u00e9al through the help of multidisciplinary artist Charles Gagnon.<ref name=\"Lamothe\">{{cite AV media\n | people = Lamothe, Michel (Director)\n | date = 2010\n | title = John Max: A Portrait\n | medium = Digital video\n | url = https://f3m.ca/film/john-max-a-portrait/\n | publisher = Les Films du 3 Mars\n | oclc = 796388003\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://charlesgagnonartist.com/artist|title=Charles Gagnon - Artist|website=Charles Gagnon|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> Gagnon had included many photographs of Max in the Christian Pavilion of [[Expo 67]], both as prints for the photographic exhibition and as animated stills in the collage movie ''Le huiti\u00e8me jour''.<ref>{{cite AV media notes\n | last = Gagnon\n | first = Monika Kin\n | date = 2009\n | type = booklet\n | title = Charles Gagnon : 4 films\n | publisher = Spectra Media\n | oclc = 429726241\n | isbn = 9780981203416\n}}</ref> Gagnon\u2019s movie was a commentary on the increasing alienation of life under the threat of nuclear war, and its use of stills recalled the movies of [[Arthur Lipsett]], another friend of Max, who himself performed in Lipsett\u2019s movies ''[[21-87]]'' and ''N-Zone''.<ref name=\"Nzone\">{{cite AV media\n | people = [[Arthur Lipsett|Lipsett, Arthur]] (Director)\n | date = 1970\n | title = N-Zone\n | medium = 16 mm\n | url = https://www.nfb.ca/film/n-zone_en/\n | publisher = National Film Board of Canada\n | oclc = 1029492677\n}}</ref>\n\nMax\u2019s acquaintance with the growing counterculture movement of the late 1960s, such as his participation to the third issue of the sexual liberation magazine ''Sexus,''<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Max |first1=John |title=John Max, photographe |journal=Sexus |language=French |date=1968 |pages=38\u201363}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montrealundergroundorigins.ca/origins-of-the-montreal-underground/|title=Origins of the Montreal Underground|last=|first=|date=|website=Montreal Underground Origins Blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> also led him to experiment with the slide show. His images were used in many happenings of the Lord Maudsley Circus of the Performing Arts,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Germain |first1=Georges-H\u00e9bert |title=Les grands spectacles |journal=SPEC, le magazine de spectacles de La Presse |language=French |date=1970 |volume=1 |issue=49 |page=10 |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2715080?docpos=9}}</ref> a light show collective created by editors of the Montr\u00e9al underground magazine ''LOGOS''.<ref>{{cite web |title=LOGOS and Montreal counter-culture |url=https://www.montrealundergroundorigins.ca/logos-and-montreal-counter-culture/?complete=1 |website=Montr\u00e9al Underground Origins Blog}}</ref> Max's slide shows for the Lord Maudsley were performed at the opening of an [[Alfred Pellan]] retrospective at the [[Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Montr\u00e9al]] on 29 April 1969<ref>{{cite news |title=Une soir\u00e9e \u2018Voir Pellan\u2019 au Mus\u00e9e d\u2019art contemporain |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2777543?docpos=9 |work=[[Le Devoir]] |language=French |date=28 April 1969}}</ref> and during [[Janis Joplin]]\u2019s 4 November 1969 concert at the [[Montr\u00e9al Forum]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leclerc |first1=Yves |title=Janis Joplin hurle, se d\u00e9cha\u00eene, et reste \u2018cool\u2019 |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2682658?docpos=8 |work=La Presse |language=French |issue=5 November 1969}}</ref>\n\n=== 1970\u20131973: Major works ===\n\nIn the early 1970s, John Max produced three major works. On 8 January 1970, he opened his second solo exhibition in Paris at the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 fran\u00e7aise de photographie]], ''Le soleil brilla toute la nuit'' (also known as ''...And the Sun Shone White All Night Long'' or ''...And the Sun It Shone White All Night Long'').<ref>{{cite news |title=John Max \u00e0 Paris |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2777762?docpos=10 |work=Le Devoir |date=9 January 1970|language=French}}</ref> 57 prints were exhibited, among Max\u2019s most expressive, in a highly charged and graphic style.<ref name=\"Lamothe\" />\n\nIn 1971, the TV documentary ''...to be INDIAN'' was broadcast by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC).<ref>{{cite news |title=Indian Philosophy Probed |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/481290057/ |work=[[Calgary Herald]] |date=26 March 1971}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref> Directed by [[Jesse Nishihata]], the movie was composed entirely of still photographs shot by Max, animated in the manner of NFB films such as ''[[City of Gold (1957 film)|City of Gold]]'', by [[Wolf Koenig]] and [[Colin Low (filmmaker)|Colin Low]] (a style that was later known as the \u201c[[Ken Burns Effect]]\u201d). The images were synchronized with interviews, and together they draw a portrait of three Indigenous communities in Alberta ([[University nuhelot\u02bc\u012fne thaiyots\u02bc\u012f nistameyim\u00e2kanak Blue Quills|Blue Quills College]], [[Frog Lake, Alberta|Frog Lake]], and [[Robert Smallboy#Smallboy Camp or Mountain Cree Camp|Smallboy Camp]]) during a tense moment in their relationships with the [[Canadian government]] about their [[Indian Register|Indian]] status, self-government, and revendications.<ref>{{cite web |title=The White Paper, 1969 |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/the-white-paper-1969 |website=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]}}</ref>\n\nFinally, in 1972 the exhibition ''Open Passport = Un passeport infini'' opened at the Photo Gallery of the NFB in [[Ottawa]].<ref name=\"NGC-OP\">{{cite web |title=Open Passport = Un passeport infini |url=http://library.gallery.ca/record=b1262304~S4 |website=Library and Archives \u2014 Catalogue |publisher=National Gallery of Canada}}</ref> A sequence of 161 black and white photographs culled from Max\u2019s archives, some dating as early as 1960, ''Open Passport'' is widely considered his most important work.<ref name=\"NGC-report\" /> The photographs are mainly portraits, of Max\u2019s family (his wife and son) and friends, many of which were established artists and personalities. Among those portrayed are [[Leonard Cohen]], [[Janis Joplin]], [[Sam Tata]], Fran\u00e7ois Dallegret, [[Vittorio Fiorucci]], Guy Borremans, Sylvain P. [Henri] Cousineau, [[Lorraine Monk]], [[Jean-Claude Germain]], [[Moondog]], [[Arthur Lipsett]], [[Frank Zappa]] and [[Gail Zappa]], Henry Zemel, Gordon Sheppard, [[Nina Raginsky]], [[Judith Eglington]], Charles Gagnon, [[Dennis Stock]], [[Martin Lavut]], [[Grace Slick]], and [[Michio Kushi]].<ref name=\"OP_BOOK\">{{cite book |last1=Max |first1=John |title=Open Pasport |date=1973 |publisher=IMPRESSIONS |location=Toronto |oclc=1118991051}}</ref>\n\nMax unified the selection for ''Open Passport'' by organizing the images according to a narrative progression, by grouping images in grids, using repetitions and a variety of sequencing strategies that can recall large-scale photographic exhibitions such as ''[[The Family of Man]]''. The underlying story is that of a couple confronting the arrival of a child: whilst the mother experiences an increasing toll on her sanity and her energy, the father confronts a dilemma between his artistic career and his family. The conflict is ultimately resolved by his departure, but this resolution is not considered a happy ending by those involved.<ref name=\"FakingDeath\">{{cite book |last1=Cousineau-Levine |first1=Penny |author1-link=Penny Cousineau-Levine |title=Faking Death: Canadian Art Photography and the Canadian Imagination |date=2003 |publisher=McGill-Queen\u2019s University Press |location=Montr\u00e9al and Kingston |isbn=0773525262 |url=https://www.mqup.ca/faking-death-products-9780773528260.php}}</ref><ref name=\"MHV-Uhl\">{{cite book |last1=Hardy-Vall\u00e9e |first1=Michel |editor1-last=Uhl |editor1-first=Magali |title=Les r\u00e9cits visuels de soi : Mises en r\u00e9cit artistiques et nouvelles sc\u00e9nographies de l\u2019intime |date=2015 |publisher=Presses universitaires de Paris ouest |language=French |location=Paris |isbn=9782840162285 |pages=197\u2013206 |url=https://presses.parisnanterre.fr/?p=2688 |chapter=Open Passport : Le r\u00e9cit photographique et le langage universel de John Max}}</ref>\n\n''Open Passport'' was accompanied by a slide show of the photographs at its opening in Ottawa and Montr\u00e9al,<ref name=\"White\">{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Michael |title=John Max: Photographs Born of a Beat Generation |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NIMuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qqEFAAAAIBAJ&hl=fr&pg=909%2C2693835 |work=The Gazette |date=10 February 1973}}</ref> and it traveled to multiple venues in Canada until 1976.<ref name=\"NGC-OP\" /> It was printed as a [[Photo-book|photobook]] by the [[Toronto]]-based magazine ''IMPRESSIONS'' as its special issue No. 6 and 7 in late 1973.<ref name=\"OP_BOOK\" /> [[A. D. Coleman|A.D. Coleman]] favourably reviewed it in the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Coleman|first1=A.D. |author1-link=A. D. Coleman|url=https://nyti.ms/1XVstnI|title=The Photography Book as Autobiography|date=11 August 1974|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=|url-status=live|page=D25}}{{subscription|s}}</ref>\n\n=== 1974\u20131995: Japan and back ===\n\nFollowing the critical success of ''Open Passport'', John Max was inducted to the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]] in 1974,<ref>{{cite web |title=Members - 1880 to the Present |url=http://www.rca-arc.ca/ |website=[[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]] |accessdate=4 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030201044301/http://www.rca-arc.ca/Members1880MtoN.htm |archivedate=1 February 2003}}</ref> and received a Senior Arts Grant from the [[Canada Council]] to travel to Japan to photograph.<ref>{{cite web |author1=[[Canada Council]] |title=1973\u201374 Annual Report |url=https://canadacouncil.ca/-/media/Files/CCA/Corporate/Annual-Reports/en/1973-74-Annual-Report.pdf |page=36}}</ref> He had long professed his interest in the country\u2019s culture and spirituality, and he stayed four years in the country, from 1974 to 1978. Unfortunately, he did not leave before the expiry of his visa, and he was arrested by the Japanese authorities, his thousands of rolls of film put in storage.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Purdie |first1=James |title=Rescue Urged for Max Film |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=11 November 1978 |ISSN=03190714}}</ref> Many of them were rendered unusable because of the storage conditions, but he eventually brought the remainder back in Canada.<ref name=\"Lamothe\" />\n\nDuring the 1980s, he did three solo exhibitions in small venues, which received limited press coverage: ''John Max: Images of Japan, 1974\u201379 Photographs'' (1982),<ref>{{cite news |last1=Daigneault |first1=Gilles |title=Les expositions / Il \u00e9tait une fois dans l\u2019est |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2769513?docpos=26 |work=Le Devoir |language=French|date=30 October 1982 |page=26}}</ref> ''On the Wings of a Mosquito: The Nothing and The Everything'' (1984) and ''Strike up the Band!'' (1986).<ref name=\"CV-MAX\">{{cite web |title=Curriculum Vitae, John Max |url=https://www.lacastiglione.ca/cv-john-max |website=La Castiglione }}</ref> In 1991 he was slated to present a career-spanning retrospective exhibition during the biennial [[Mois de la Photo \u00e0 Montr\u00e9al]], but he failed to the task, and delivered only two photographs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dumont |first1=Jean |title=Autres figurations |language=French |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2760934?docpos=12 |work=Le Devoir |date=28 September 1991 |page=12}}</ref> His photos were occasionally included in group exhibitions, and he showed some of his drawings in 1995.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cou\u00eblle |first1=Jennifer |title=Une affaire de tomates\u2026 |language=French |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2771399?docpos=10 |work=Le Devoir |date=19 October 1995 |page=B10}}</ref>\n\n=== 1997\u20132011: Rediscovery and final years ===\n\nIn the late 1990s, through the efforts of the Stephen Bulger Gallery in Toronto, and VOX in Montr\u00e9al, John Max exhibited photographs from ''Open Passport'', from Japan, and from ''On the Wings of a Mosquito'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Allaire |first1=Serge |title=John Max |journal=Ciel variable |date=Fall 1997 |volume=40 |language=French |url=http://cielvariable.ca/numeros/ciel-variable-40-releve-quebec-canada/john-max-serge-allaire/}}</ref> this time to greater critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lehman |first1=Henry |title=Echo is Heard from Career of a Talented Photographer |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/425049412 |work=The Gazette |date=5 April 1997}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref> The Mus\u00e9e de la Photographie \u00e0 [[Charleroi]], in [[Belgium]], showed his photographs and printed a catalogue, ''Quelque chose suit son cours = Something is taking its place'' (1998).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Max |first1=John |last2=Vercheval |first2=Georges |title=Quelque chose suit son cours = Something is Taking its Place |date=1998 |language=French,English |publisher=Mus\u00e9e de la photographie \u00e0 Charleroi |location=Charleroi, Belgium |isbn=9782871830306 |oclc=757584367}}</ref> Max was also part of the 1999 edition of the [[Noorderlicht]] Fotofestival in [[Groningen]], [[Netherlands]], and four photographs from ''Open Passport'' were printed in the catalogue, ''Wonderland''.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Melis |editor1-first=Wim |editor2-last=Botman |editor2-first=Machiel|title=Noorderlicht: Wonderland |date=1999 |publisher=Stichting Aurora Borealis |location=Groningen, Netherlands |isbn=9789076703039 |oclc=905439783}}</ref>\n\nDuring the early 2000s, his photos appeared in retrospective thematic group exhibitions of the [[Canadian Museum of Contemporary Photography]], the [[Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Montr\u00e9al|Mus\u00e9e d\u2019art contemporain de Montr\u00e9al]], and the [[Montr\u00e9al Museum of Fine Arts]].<ref name=\"CV-MAX\" /> Two projects concurrently attempted to sketch a biography of Max,\n{{ill|David Homel's|fr|David Homel}} [[essay]] ''Le monde est un document'' (2002), and [[Michel Lamothe]]\u2019s [[documentary film]] ''John Max: A Portrait'' (2010).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Homel |first1=David |last2=Homel |first2=David |title=Le monde est un document |date=2002 |publisher=\u00c9ditions J\u2019ai VU |location=Qu\u00e9bec City |isbn=9782922763041 |oclc=747175727 |language=French,English}}</ref><ref name=\"Lamothe\" /> Lamothe\u2019s movie was filmed around the time Max was being evicted from his house in 2003 and shows him in dire straits.\n\nThe sale of a complete set of exhibition prints of the original ''Open Passport'' exhibition to the Canadian Museum of Contemporary Photography afforded Max some financial security,<ref name=\"NGC-report\" /> while the support of his friends\u2014Lamothe, {{ill|Gabor Szilasi|fr}}, [[Claude Chamberland]] among others\u2014allowed the emptying of his overstuffed house and the safeguard of his photographic materials.<ref name=\"Block\" />\n\nHe lived in a Buddhist ashram for the final years of his life and died on 5 May 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nadeau |first1=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois |title=D\u00e9c\u00e8s du photographe John Max |language=French |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2929895?docpos=9 |work=Le Devoir |date=7 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nJohn Max was married to medical illustrator Janet Peace (1933\u20132011). They had one son, David, to whom is dedicated ''Open Passport''.<ref name=\"OP_BOOK\" /> They divorced a few years following their marriage; Peace then lived in Mexico and Canada with her son and her second husband.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Loth |first1=Marlene |title=Janet Perez-Vela (obituray) |journal=BMCAAnewsletter |date=Spring 2012 |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=27\u20138 |publisher=Biomedical Communications Alumni Association |location=University of Toronto}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\nMany photographers and artists such as Benoit Aquin<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ewing |first1=William A. |title=Benoit Aquin: Fire & Ice = Benoit Aquin : De feu et de glace |journal=Ciel variable |date=2009 |pages=25\u201331 |url=https://id.erudit.org/iderudit/549ac|language=English,French}}</ref> and [[Marc S\u00e9guin (painter)|Marc S\u00e9guin]]<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Pichette |editor1-first=Jean |title=Marc S\u00e9guin : survol overview |date=2006 |publisher=[[Les 400 coups]] |location=Montr\u00e9al |isbn=9782895402091 |oclc=71186547|language=French,English}}</ref> have underlined the importance of John Max and of his works.\n\n''Open Passport'' has also been referenced by various works:\n* ''Mona Nima'' (1977) by Sylvain P. Cousineau.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cousineau |first1=Sylvain P. |title=Mona Nima |date=1977 |publisher=Powys Press |location=Almonte, ON |isbn=9780969062806 |url=https://www.cousineau.org/photographie#/mona-nima-xxxx/ |oclc=4048545}}</ref>\n* The artist book ''Hommage'' (2005) by Serge Cl\u00e9ment contains both a copy of ''Open Passport'' and Cl\u00e9ment\u2019s reinterpretation of it as an extended sequence.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cl\u00e9ment|first1=Serge|url=http://www.sergeclement.com/hommage-john-max-open-passport/|title=Hommage : John Max\u2014Open Passport|date=2005|publisher=S. Cl\u00e9ment|year=|isbn=|location=Montr\u00e9al|pages=|oclc=62430203}}</ref>\n* Composer [[Christopher Mayo]] has released ''To Discard all Images'' (2019), a piece for voice and instruments combining recordings of the reactions of photographers to ''Open Passport'' with Mayo\u2019s original score.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mayo |first1=Christopher |author1-link=Christopher Mayo|title=To Discard All Images |url=https://soundcloud.com/christophermayo/to-discard-all-images}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Exhibitions ===\nSince many of the following exhibitions also [[Travelling exhibition|traveled]] to a multiplicity of sites over many years, only the opening place and year are indicated.\n\n==== Solo ====\n* '''1960''' ''John Max Shouts: Enough, No More, I Want'', McGill University, Montr\u00e9al\n* '''1970''' ''Le soleil brilla toute la nuit = And the Sun It Shone White All Night Long'', Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Fran\u00e7aise de Photographie, Paris\n* '''1972''' ''Open Passport = Un passeport infini'', The NFB Photo Gallery, Ottawa\n* '''1982''' ''John Max: Images of Japan, 1974\u201379 Photographs'', A.R. Encadrements, Montr\u00e9al\n* '''1984''' ''On the Wings of a Mosquito: The Nothing and The Everything'', Dazibao, Montr\u00e9al\n* '''1986''' ''Strike up the Band!'', The Art Workshop, Montr\u00e9al\n* '''1997''' ''Swallowing a Diamond'', Stephen Bulger Gallery, Toronto\n* '''1997''' ''Open Passport'', VOX, Montr\u00e9al\n\n==== Selected group exhibitions ====\n* '''1957''' Photographie 57, Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al\n* '''1963''' Photography 63 / An International Exhibition, George Eastman House\n* '''1967''' 5<sup>e</sup> Biennale de Paris, [[Mus\u00e9e d'Art Moderne de Paris|Mus\u00e9e d'art moderne de Paris]]\n* '''1967''' Universal and International Exhibition, Montreal Expo \u201967\n* '''1967''' Bytown International Photographic Exhibition, Camera Club of Ottawa<ref>{{cite book |title=Bytown International 1967 Exposition photographique Canada |date=1967 |publisher=Camera Club of Ottawa|oclc=80536898|language=English,French}}</ref>\n* '''1967''' Photography in Canada 1967 = Photographie au Canada 1967, NFB\n* '''1968''' Other Places = Sous d\u2019autres cieux, NFB\n* '''1969''' Seeds of the spacefields = Cela commen\u00e7a par un r\u00eave et ce fut la cr\u00e9ation, NFB\n* '''1969''' Image 6: Photography in Canada 1969 = Photographie au Canada 1969, NFB\n* '''1969''' Quatre photographes montr\u00e9alais: Marc-Andr\u00e9 Gagn\u00e9, Ronald Labelle, John Max, Michel Saint-Jean = Four Montreal Photographers, National Gallery of Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Four Montreal photographers |url=http://library.gallery.ca/record=b1125748~S4 |website=National Gallery of Canada}}</ref>\n* '''1999''' Wonderland, Noorderlicht Photofestival\n\n=== Publications ===\n\n==== Monographs ====\n{{refbegin|indent=yes}}\n* '''1973''' {{cite book |last1=Max |first1=John |title=Open Pasport  |publisher=IMPRESSIONS |location=Toronto |oclc=1118991051}}\n* '''1998''' {{cite book |last1=Max |first1=John |last2=Vercheval |first2=Georges |title=Quelque chose suit son cours = Something is Taking its Place |publisher=Mus\u00e9e de la photographie \u00e0 Charleroi |location=Charleroi, Belgium |isbn=9782871830306 |oclc=757584367|language=French,English}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==== Collective works ====\n{{refbegin|indent=yes|}}\n* '''1957''' {{cite book|last1=Millet|first1=Robert|title=quelques uns des travaux expos\u00e9s d\u2019abord \u00e0 l\u2019Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al en f\u00e9vrier \u201957 par un groupe qui croit que la photographie est autre chose qu\u2019un m\u00e9dium impersonnel de reproduction\u2026|oclc=938043393|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Artistique de l\u2019Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al|year=|isbn=|location=Montr\u00e9al|language=French|pages=}}\n* '''1963''' {{cite book|last=|first=|title=Photography 63 / An International Exhibition|publisher=George Eastman House|year=|isbn=|location=Rochester, NY|pages=|oclc=613432467}}\n* '''1968''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor-last1=Monk|editor-first1=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Call them Canadians: A Photographic Point of View|publisher=Queen\u2019s Printer|year=|location=Ottawa|pages=|oclc=622822727}}\n* '''1968''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor-last1=Monk|editor-first1=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Ces visages qui sont un pays|publisher=Imprimeur de la Reine|year=|location=Ottawa|pages=|language=French|oclc=604354983}}\n* '''1968''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor1-last=Monk|editor1-first=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Photography = Photographie Canada 1967|publisher=National Film Board of Canada|year=|location=Ottawa|pages=|oclc=191407|series=IMAGE vol. 2|language=English,French}}\n* '''1968''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor1-last=Monk|editor1-first=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Other Places = Sous d\u2019autres cieux|publisher=National Film Board of Canada|year=|location=Ottawa|pages=|oclc=30071341|series=IMAGE vol. 3|language=English,French}}\n* '''1969''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor1-last=Monk|editor1-first=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Seeds of the spacefields (a sequence of ten dreams) = cela commen\u00e7a par un r\u00eave et ce fut la Cr\u00e9ation (une s\u00e9rie de dix r\u00eaves)|publisher=Martlet Press|year=|location=Toronto|pages=|oclc=62931108|series=IMAGE vol. 5|language=English,French}}\n* '''1970''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor1-last=Monk|editor1-first=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Image 6: A Review of Contemporary Photography in Canada = Une revue de la photographie contemporaine au Canada|publisher=Martlet Press|year=|location=Toronto|pages=|oclc=1131342409|series=IMAGE vol. 6|language=English,French}}\n* '''1999''' {{cite book|editor1-last=Melis|editor1-first=Wim|editor2-last=Botman|editor2-first=Machiel|last=|first=|title=Noorderlicht: Wonderland|publisher=Stichting Aurora Borealis|location=Groningen, Netherlands|pages=|year=|isbn=9789076703039|oclc=905439783}}\n* '''2002''' {{cite book|editor1-last=Pichette|editor1-first=Jean|last=|first=|title=Les tours de Babel : La paix apr\u00e8s le 11 septembre|publisher=Les 400 coups|location=Montr\u00e9al|pages=|year=|language=French|isbn=9782895400813|oclc=61445224|series=Sortir la t\u00eate}}\n* '''2002''' {{cite book|last1=Homel|first1=David|last2=Homel|first2=David|title=Le monde est un document|publisher=\u00c9ditions J\u2019ai VU|location=Qu\u00e9bec City|pages=|year=|isbn=9782922763041|oclc=747175727|language=French,English}}\n* '''2005''' {{cite book|last1=Cl\u00e9ment|first1=Serge|title=Hommage : John Max\u2014Open Passport|publisher=S. Cl\u00e9ment|year=|isbn=|location=Montr\u00e9al|pages=|url=http://www.sergeclement.com/hommage-john-max-open-passport/|oclc=62430203}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==== Selected photo-essays ====\n{{refbegin|indent=yes}}\n* '''1960''' {{cite news\n| last         = Trent\n| first        = Bill\n| date         = 15 October 1960\n| title        = Alfred Pellan: Lover of Life and Art\n| url          = https://www.newspapers.com/image/457008538/\n| work         = Weekend Magazine\n}}{{subscription|s}}\n* '''1961''' {{cite news\n| last         = Max\n| first        = John\n| date         = 22 April 1961\n| title        = The Last Bohemia\n| url          = https://archive.macleans.ca/issue/19610422#!&pid=24\n| work         = Maclean's\n}}\n* '''1961''' {{cite news\n| last         = Bouthillette\n| first        = Jean\n| date         = 24 June 1961\n| title        = La Roulotte prom\u00e8ne ses personnages de parc en parc\n| url          = http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/3292625?docpos=6\n| work         = Perspectives\n|language=French\n}}\n* '''1961''' {{cite journal |last1=Saucier |first1=Pierre |title=Jeunes peintres au travail |journal=Vie des arts |date=1961 |volume=22 |pages=37\u201345 |url=https://id.erudit.org/iderudit/55199ac}}\n* '''1963''' {{cite news\n| last         = Max\n| first        = John\n| date         = 6 July 1961\n| title        = Some Indians with no White Problem \u2014 Yet\n| url          = http://archive.theadcc.ca/islandora/object/adcc%3A52550\n| work         = Maclean's\n}}\n* '''1966''' {{cite news\n| last         = Ruddy\n| first        = Jon\n| date         = 1 October 1966\n| title        = Is the World (Or Anybody) Ready for Leonard Cohen?\n| url          = https://archive.macleans.ca/article/1966/10/1/is-the-world-or-anybody-ready-for-leonard-cohen-\n| work         = Maclean's\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n=== Filmography ===\n\n==== As himself ====\n* '''1999''' Chiasson, Herm\u00e9n\u00e9gilde, dir. ''Photography: Eleven Artists from Canada = Photographies : onze artistes du Canada''. National Film Board of Canada = Office National du Film du Canada. Video, 48 min. {{OCLC|757485490}}\n* '''2006''' Lavut, Martin, dir. ''[[Remembering Arthur]]''. National Film Board of Canada = Office National du Film du Canada. Video, 89 min.\n* '''2010''' Lamothe, Michel, dir. ''[https://f3m.ca/film/john-max-a-portrait/ John Max: A Portrait]''. Les Films du 3 Mars. Digital video, 94 min.\n\n==== As actor ====\n* '''1964''' Lipsett, Arthur, dir. ''[[21-87]]''. National Film Board of Canada = Office National du Film du Canada. 16 mm, 9 min.\n* '''1970''' Lipsett, Arthur, dir. ''[https://www.onf.ca/film/n-zone_en/ N-Zone]''. National Film Board of Canada = Office National du Film du Canada. 16 mm, 45 min.\n\n==== As photographer ====\n* '''1967''' Gagnon, Charles, dir. ''Le huiti\u00e8me jour = The Eighth Day''. 16 mm, 13 min. {{ISBN| 9780981203416}} {{OCLC| 429726241}}\n* '''1971''' Nishihata, Jesse [Hideo], dir. ''...to be INDIAN''. Canadian Broadcasting Corporation. 16 mm, 54 min.\n\n== Collections ==\n* [[Canada Council]] Art Bank<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://banquedart.ca/art-piece/-6-from-on-the-wings-of-a-mosquito--89_90-0270?author=Max%20John&name=%236%20%28from%20On%20the%20Wings%20of%20a%20Mosquito%29%20%20%20%20%20&year=1989#f:@category_f=Photographie|title=Canada Council Art Bank|website=artbank.ca}}</ref>\n* [[Carleton University]] Art Gallery,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cuag.ca/index.php/collections/photography/|title=Carleton University Art Gallery|website=www.cuag.ca}}</ref> Ottawa<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://app.pch.gc.ca/application/artefacts_hum/re_as.app?t=5&i=false&n=0&p=a&o=aia&f=ar.i&k=Max%2C+John1i1Carleton&pID=12&r=50&s=s&v=ar&l=l&lang=en|title=Artefacts Canada|website=app.pch.gc.ca}}</ref>\n* [[Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que Qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise]], Montr\u00e9al<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.cinematheque.qc.ca/recherche/recherche/en/multi?operator%5B0%5D=%2B&q%5B0%5D=%22John+Max%22&field%5B0%5D=*&core=oeuvres|title=Recherche collections (b\u00eata) &#124; La Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://app.pch.gc.ca/application/artefacts_hum/re_as.app?t=5&i=false&n=0&p=a&o=aia&f=ar.i&k=Max%2C+John1i1Cin%C3%A9math%C3%A8que&pID=1&r=50&s=s&v=ar&l=l&lang=en|title=Artefacts Canada|website=app.pch.gc.ca}}</ref>\n* [[National Gallery of Canada]], Ottawa<ref name=\"NGC-Max\"/>\n* [[Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Montr\u00e9al]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://app.pch.gc.ca/application/artefacts_hum/re_as.app?lang=en&t=5&i=false&n=0&p=a&o=aia&f=i.ar&k=Mus%C3%A9e+d%27art+contemporain1i1Max%2C+John&pID=1&r=50&s=s&v=none&l=l|title=Artefacts Canada|website=app.pch.gc.ca}}</ref>\n* {{ill|Mus\u00e9e d'art de Joliette|fr}}, QC<ref>{{cite web |title=Collection |url=https://www.museejoliette.org/fr/collections/?artistes=13596 |website=Mus\u00e9e d'art de Joliette}}</ref>\n* [[Mus\u00e9e des beaux-arts de Montr\u00e9al]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://app.pch.gc.ca/application/artefacts_hum/re_as.app?lang=en&t=5&i=false&n=0&p=a&o=aia&f=i.ar&k=Mus%C3%A9e+des+beaux-arts+de+Montr%C3%A9al1i1Max%2C+John&pID=1&r=50&s=s&v=none&l=l|title=Artefacts Canada|website=app.pch.gc.ca}}</ref>\n* [[Mus\u00e9e national des beaux-arts du Qu\u00e9bec]], Qu\u00e9bec City<ref>{{cite web |title=John Max |url=https://collections.mnbaq.org/fr/artiste/600014159 |website=Mus\u00e9e national des beaux-arts du Qu\u00e9bec|lang=fr}}</ref>\n* [[Winnipeg Art Gallery]], MB<ref>{{cite web |title=John Max |url=https://wag.ca/art/collections/search/?q=john+max |website=Winnipeg Art Gallery}}</ref>\n* [[George Eastman Museum]], Rochester, NY<ref>{{cite web |title=John Max |url=https://collections.eastman.org/people/40405/john-max |website=George Eastman Museum}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://rca-arc.ca/who-we-are/members/members-since-1880/ List of members, Royal Canadian Academy of the Arts]\n* [https://www.gallery.ca/collection/artist/john-max National Gallery of Canada]\n* [https://www.bulgergallery.com/ Stephen Bulger Gallery]\n* [http://www.centrevox.ca/fd/artiste_select.php?artiste=66 VOX, Centre de l'image contemporaine]\n* [https://www.lacastiglione.ca/john-max Galerie La Castiglione]\n\n{{Authority control |VIAF=52934352 |LCCN=n/77/006662 |ISNI=0000 0001 1763 5828 |GND=174341776 |WORLDCATID=lccn-n77006662}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Max, John}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian photographers]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Quebec people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Artists from Quebec]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian photographers]]\n[[Category:Canadian photojournalists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]]\n[[Category:National Film Board of Canada people]]\n[[Category:Photography in Canada]]\n[[Category:Photography in Japan]]\n[[Category:Street photographers]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian diaspora in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = John Max\n| honorific_suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|RCA}}\n| birth_name       = John Porchawka\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|year=1936|month=September|day=23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Montr\u00e9al]], [[Canada]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2011|05|05|1936|09|23|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Montr\u00e9al]], [[Canada]]\n| nationality      = Canadian\n| education        = School of Art and Design, [[Mus\u00e9e des beaux-arts de Montr\u00e9al]]\n| known_for        = Photography, film\n| notable_works    = ''Le soleil brilla toute la nuit'' (1970)<br />''...to be INDIAN'' (1971)<br />''Open Passport'' (1972)\n| style            = Portrait, sequence\n| awards           = {{awd|Dipl\u00f4me d\u2019honneur and M\u00e9daille de bronze de la ville de [[Bordeaux]] |(1972)|||}}\n{{awd|[[National Film Board of Canada]] Gold Medal for Excellence in Photography|(1972)|||}}\n| elected          = [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]] (1974)\n}}\n\n'''John Max''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|RCA}} (born '''John Porchawka'''; 23 September 1936 \u2013 5 May 2011) was a Canadian photojournalist, photography teacher, and art photographer. He is recognized for his use of the narrative sequence, his expressive portraiture, and his intensely personal, subjective approach to photography.\n\nHe grew up in [[Montr\u00e9al]], where he participated in the visual arts scene of the city during the late 1950s and early 1960s, and published numerous photo-essays for newspapers and magazines. He also maintained close ties to the American photography scene.\n\nMax was championed during the 1960s and 1970s by the [[National Film Board of Canada]], through its [[National Film Board of Canada#Still Photography Division|Still Photography Division]], and the [[National Gallery of Canada]], through a variety of exhibition and publication projects. Gradually abandoning photojournalism during the 1960s, he focused his work on photographic art exhibitions and publications. His best-known work, ''Open Passport'' (exhibited 1972\u20131976; published 1973) is a long sequence that combined photographs from diverse sources shot over the span of a decade into a unified, poetical narrative.\n\nFollowing a long trip to [[Japan]] (1974\u20131978) that resulted in his deportation and the loss of many rolls of films, he became less visible than before on the arts scene in Canada. During the late 1990s and early 2000s, he benefitted from a regain of interest in his work, before his death in 2011.\n\nThe work of John Max has been recognized by a number of critics, curators, artists, and photographers in Canada and abroad. It has also been the source of a number of responses and homages. [[Robert Frank]] said about him \"When I think of Canadian photography, his name comes up first.\"<ref name=\"Manford\">{{cite journal |last1=Manford |first1=Steven |title=Of Passports and Visas |journal=[[Canadian Art (magazine)|Canadian Art]] |date=1997 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=56 |url=https://canadianart.ca/issues/fall-1997/ |issn=08253854}}</ref>\n== Early years ==\n\nJohn Max was born John Porchawka to the family of Anna (n\u00e9e Barchynska) and Paul Porchawka, both immigrants of [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] origins, on 23 September 1936 in Montr\u00e9al.<ref name=\"NGC-Max\">{{cite web |title=John Max |url=https://www.gallery.ca/collection/artist/john-max |website=[[National Gallery of Canada]]}}</ref> His family lived in the multicultural area around [[The Main]], until they moved to the [[Rosemont\u2013La Petite-Patrie|Rosemont]] neighbourhood, where Max spent the greater part of his life.<ref name=\"Block\">{{cite news |last1=Block |first1=Irwin |title=Photographer finds a home |url=https://montrealgazette.newspapers.com/image/425515179/ |work=[[Montreal Gazette|The Gazette]] |date=24 April 2003}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref>\n\nDuring high school, he attended the [[Montr\u00e9al Museum of Fine Arts]] School of Arts and Design. Headed by [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] painter [[Arthur Lismer]], the School offered both adult and children classes taught by career artists on a variety of media, such as textile, painting, typography, graphic arts, drawing, or design.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Grigor |first1=Angela |title=Arthur Lismer, Visionary Art Educator |date=2002 |publisher=[[McGill-Queen's University Press]] |location=Montr\u00e9al and Kingston |isbn=9780773522954 |page=176 |url=https://www.mqup.ca/arthur-lismer--visionary-art-educator-products-9780773522954.php}}</ref> Porchawka distinguished himself and won scholarships for his standing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prizes, Scholarships Given At School of Art and Design |url=https://montrealgazette.newspapers.com/image/419591639/ |work=The Gazette |date=7 April 1952 |page=13}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref> He had also started taking photographs with a [[Kodak Pony 135]].<ref name=\"FotoCanada\">{{cite journal |last1=Tata |first1=Sam |author-link1=Sam Tata|title=On assignment: John Max by Sam Tata |journal=Foto-Canada |volume=I |issue=3 |date=1968 |pages=29\u201335 |oclc=173996291}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduating from high school, Porchawka studied at the [[McGill Conservatory]] but quickly abandoned his studies and focused instead on photography.<ref name=\"FotoCanada\" /> He cited the work of [[Henri Cartier-Bresson]] and [[Lutz Dille]] in [[photojournalism]] and [[street photography]] as early models. Through his frequentation of the Montr\u00e9al [[Bohemianism|bohemia]] in caf\u00e9s such as L\u2019\u00c9chourie,<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =  [[Jean Palardy|Palardy, Jean]] (Director)\n | date = 1954\n | title = Artist in Montreal\n | medium = 16 mm\n | url = https://www.onf.ca/film/artist_in_montreal/\n | time = 11:29\n | publisher = [[National Film Board of Canada]]\n | oclc = 1078057077\n}}</ref> he became acquainted with a number of artistic figures in the field of painting, sculpture, writing, theatre, cinema, and photography.<ref name=\"FotoCanada\" /><ref name=\"JCG_FN\">{{cite book |last1=Germain |first1=Jean-Claude |author-link1=Jean-Claude Germain |title=La femme nue habillait la nuit : Nouvelles historiettes de la boh\u00e8me |language=French |date=2010 |publisher=Hurtubise |location=Montr\u00e9al |isbn=9782896473144 |url=https://editionshurtubise.com/livre/la-femme-nue-habillait-la-nuit/}}</ref> For many years he photographed Montr\u00e9al artists intensively, hoping to produce a \u201cportrait of the bohemia.\u201d<ref name=\"JCG_FN\" /> This general direction yielded material for his first exhibitions and publications under the name \u201cJohn Max.\u201d Max\u2019s magazine output slowed down during the second half of the 1960s, and his practice took a turn primarily toward art photography for the rest of his career.\n\n=== 1957\u20131965: Montr\u00e9al bohemia ===\n\nIn 1957, John Max contributed a short photographic sequence and a portrait to the group exhibition ''Photographie 57'' at [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]].<ref name=\"Photo57\">{{cite book |last1=Millet |first1=Robert |title=quelques uns des travaux expos\u00e9s d\u2019abord \u00e0 l\u2019Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al en f\u00e9vrier \u201957 par un groupe qui croit que la photographie est autre chose qu\u2019un m\u00e9dium impersonnel de reproduction\u2026 |date=1957 |language=French |oclc=938043393 |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Artistique de l\u2019Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al |location=Montr\u00e9al}}</ref> It was an anticipated response to the visit of the [[MoMA]] exhibition ''[[The Family of Man]]'' later that year at the [[Montreal Museum of Fine Arts]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hone |first1=Marie-Sol |title=Exposition de photographies |journal=Quartier Latin |date=21 February 1957 |page=5 |language=French |issn=0832-4131}}</ref> Championing photography as an art form, the exhibition counted among its participants [[Claude Jutra]], [[Michel Brault]], John Max, [[Vittorio Fiorucci]], Jauran ([[Rodolphe de Repentigny]]), [[Jean-Paul Mousseau]], Gordon Webber, and many others.<ref name=\"Photo57\" /> Around the same time,  Max reached out to the [[George Eastman House]] with the help of [[Sam Tata]] and [[Vittorio Fiorucci]]. He met [[Nathan Lyons]], who supported him throughout his career and included him in the GEH exhibition ''Photography 63.''<ref name=\"NGC-report\">{{cite book |title=Touching Canadians: Annual Report 2002\u20132003 |publisher=National Gallery of Canada |location=Ottawa |page=30 |url=https://www.gallery.ca/sites/default/files/documents/planning%20and%20reporting/02-03annual_e.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Confino\">{{cite news |last1=Confino |first1=Barbara |title=Intimate Images |work=[[The Montreal Star]] |date=7 October 1972 |page=C5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Photography 63 / An International Exhibition |date=1963 |publisher=George Eastman House |location=Rochester, NY |oclc=613432467}}</ref>\n\nJohn Max\u2019s first solo exhibition opened in 1960 at [[McGill University]], but it was promptly censored and shut down: ''John Max Shouts: Enough, No More, I Want'' was relocated to a private club nearby.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sarrazin |first1=Jean |title=Des jeunes de mille ans et des jeunes d\u2019aujourd\u2019hui\u2026 |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2755656?docpos=36 |work=[[La Presse (Canadian newspaper)|La Presse]] |date=5 March 1960 |language=French |page=36}}</ref> It featured, among other sequences, a performance of modernist dancer [[Suzanne Rivest]] cast as stations of the cross, a suggestion of Max\u2019s friend [[Jean-Claude Germain]].<ref name=\"JCG_FN\" />\n\nMax had become by then a regular contributor to magazines and newspaper supplements, providing photo-essays about the Montr\u00e9al artistic scene for ''[[Maclean\u2019s]]'', ''Perspectives'', ''{{ill|Vie des arts|fr}}'', and ''Weekend Magazine'', photographing among others [[Jacques Hurtubise (painter)|Jacques Hurtubise]], [[Rita Letendre]], Laure Major, Marcella Maltais, [[Suzanne Meloche]], [[Robert Roussil]] and [[Armand Vaillancourt]]. His portrait of poet [[Leonard Cohen]] also adorned the cover of the first edition of ''[[The Spice-Box of Earth]]'' (1961). Most notably, he contributed to ''Maclean\u2019s'' a reportage on the Montr\u00e9al artistic scene, \u201cThe Last Bohemia,\u201d<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Max |first1=John |title=The Last Bohemia |journal=[[Maclean's]] |date=22 April 1961 |pages=24\u201327 |url=https://archive.macleans.ca/issue/19610422#!&pid=24}}</ref> and another about the [[Cree]] [[Mistissini, Quebec|community]] of [[Lake Mistassini]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Max |first1=John |title=Some Indians with no White Problem \u2014 Yet |journal=Maclean's |date=6 July 1963 |pages=22\u201324}}</ref> The latter helped establish his reputation<ref>{{cite web |title=1964 Editorial Art, Picture Story |url=http://archive.theadcc.ca/islandora/object/adcc%3A52550 |website=Advertising & Design Club of Canada}}</ref> and draw the attention of [[Lorraine Monk]], executive producer of the [[National Film Board of Canada#Still Photography Division|Still Photography Division]] of the [[National Film Board of Canada]].\n\n=== 1966\u20131970: Institutional recognition and underground ===\n\nThe [[National Film Board of Canada#Still Photography Division|SPD]] acquired some of Max\u2019s photographs from [[Mistissini, Quebec|Mistassini (today Mistissini, Quebec)]] in 1965,<ref>{{cite web |title=Mistassini, John Max |url=https://www.gallery.ca/collection/search-the-collection?search_api_views_fulltext=john+max+mistassini&sort_by=search_api_relevance&f%5B0%5D=field_reference_artist%253Atitle%3AJohn+Max&f%5B1%5D=field_date_made_earliest_year%3A%5B1960+TO+1979%5D |website=National Gallery of Canada}}</ref> and he did a number of assignments for the Division over the following years. This got him included in a series of NFB publications, starting with the [[Canadian Centennial]] books ''Call Them Canadians'' and ''Ces visages qui sont un pays'' (1968),<ref>{{cite book |editor-last1=Monk |editor-first1=Lorraine |editor-link1=Lorraine Monk |title=Call them Canadians: A Photographic Point of View |date=1968 |publisher=Queen\u2019s Printer |location=Ottawa |oclc=622822727}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor-last1=Monk |editor-first1=Lorraine |title=Ces visages qui sont un pays |date=1968 |language=French |publisher=Imprimeur de la Reine |location=Ottawa |oclc=604354983}}</ref> as well as exhibition catalogues in the IMAGE series (1967\u20131970).<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Monk |editor1-first=Lorraine\n|title=Photography = Photographie Canada 1967\n|date=1968\n|publisher=National Film Board of Canada\n|location=Ottawa\n|oclc=191407\n|series=IMAGE vol. 2 |language=English,French\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Monk |editor1-first=Lorraine\n|title=Other Places = Sous d\u2019autres cieux\n|date=1968\n|publisher=National Film Board of Canada\n|location=Ottawa\n|oclc= 30071341\n|series=IMAGE vol. 3 |language=English,French\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Monk |editor1-first=Lorraine\n|title=Seeds of the spacefields (a sequence of ten dreams) = cela commen\u00e7a par un r\u00eave et ce fut la Cr\u00e9ation (une s\u00e9rie de dix r\u00eaves)\n|date=1969\n|publisher=Martlet Press\n|location=Toronto\n|oclc=62931108\n|series=IMAGE vol. 5 |language=English,French\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Monk |editor1-first=Lorraine\n|title=Image 6: A Review of Contemporary Photography in Canada = Une revue de la photographie contemporaine au Canada\n|date=1970\n|publisher=Martlet Press\n|location=Toronto\n|oclc=1131342409\n|series=IMAGE vol. 6 |language=English,French\n}}</ref> The National Gallery of Canada also supported him, and he was chosen in 1967 to represent Canada at the [[Biennale de Paris|5<sup>e</sup> Biennale de Paris]], alongside sculptor [[Henry Saxe]], engraver Pierre H\u00e9bert, and filmmaker [[Al Sens]]. Max presented a sequence of six photographs on the imposed theme of the fantastic, for which he was awarded a [[French franc|1000 F]] prize.<ref>{{cite book |title=Cinqui\u00e8me biennale de Paris |publisher=[[Mus\u00e9e d'Art Moderne de Paris|Mus\u00e9e d\u2019art moderne de Paris]] |location=Paris |language=French |oclc=983760774 |page=46}}</ref>\n\nHe was included in numerous group exhibitions in Canada, traveled to [[England]] and [[France]], and was appointed as a teacher in photography at [[Loyola College (Montreal)|Loyola College]] in Montr\u00e9al through the help of multidisciplinary artist Charles Gagnon.<ref name=\"Lamothe\">{{cite AV media\n | people = Lamothe, Michel (Director)\n | date = 2010\n | title = John Max: A Portrait\n | medium = Digital video\n | url = https://f3m.ca/film/john-max-a-portrait/\n | publisher = Les Films du 3 Mars\n | oclc = 796388003\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://charlesgagnonartist.com/artist|title=Charles Gagnon - Artist|website=Charles Gagnon|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> Gagnon had included many photographs of Max in the Christian Pavilion of [[Expo 67]], both as prints for the photographic exhibition and as animated stills in the collage movie ''Le huiti\u00e8me jour''.<ref>{{cite AV media notes\n | last = Gagnon\n | first = Monika Kin\n | date = 2009\n | type = booklet\n | title = Charles Gagnon : 4 films\n | publisher = Spectra Media\n | oclc = 429726241\n | isbn = 9780981203416\n}}</ref> Gagnon\u2019s movie was a commentary on the increasing alienation of life under the threat of nuclear war, and its use of stills recalled the movies of [[Arthur Lipsett]], another friend of Max, who himself performed in Lipsett\u2019s movies ''[[21-87]]'' and ''N-Zone''.<ref name=\"Nzone\">{{cite AV media\n | people = [[Arthur Lipsett|Lipsett, Arthur]] (Director)\n | date = 1970\n | title = N-Zone\n | medium = 16 mm\n | url = https://www.nfb.ca/film/n-zone_en/\n | publisher = National Film Board of Canada\n | oclc = 1029492677\n}}</ref>\n\nMax\u2019s acquaintance with the growing counterculture movement of the late 1960s, such as his participation to the third issue of the sexual liberation magazine ''Sexus,''<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Max |first1=John |title=John Max, photographe |journal=Sexus |language=French |date=1968 |pages=38\u201363}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montrealundergroundorigins.ca/origins-of-the-montreal-underground/|title=Origins of the Montreal Underground|last=|first=|date=|website=Montreal Underground Origins Blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> also led him to experiment with the slide show. His images were used in many happenings of the Lord Maudsley Circus of the Performing Arts,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Germain |first1=Georges-H\u00e9bert |title=Les grands spectacles |journal=SPEC, le magazine de spectacles de La Presse |language=French |date=1970 |volume=1 |issue=49 |page=10 |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2715080?docpos=9}}</ref> a light show collective created by editors of the Montr\u00e9al underground magazine ''LOGOS''.<ref>{{cite web |title=LOGOS and Montreal counter-culture |url=https://www.montrealundergroundorigins.ca/logos-and-montreal-counter-culture/?complete=1 |website=Montr\u00e9al Underground Origins Blog}}</ref> Max's slide shows for the Lord Maudsley were performed at the opening of an [[Alfred Pellan]] retrospective at the [[Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Montr\u00e9al]] on 29 April 1969<ref>{{cite news |title=Une soir\u00e9e \u2018Voir Pellan\u2019 au Mus\u00e9e d\u2019art contemporain |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2777543?docpos=9 |work=[[Le Devoir]] |language=French |date=28 April 1969}}</ref> and during [[Janis Joplin]]\u2019s 4 November 1969 concert at the [[Montr\u00e9al Forum]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leclerc |first1=Yves |title=Janis Joplin hurle, se d\u00e9cha\u00eene, et reste \u2018cool\u2019 |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2682658?docpos=8 |work=La Presse |language=French |issue=5 November 1969}}</ref>\n\n=== 1970\u20131973: Major works ===\n\nIn the early 1970s, John Max produced three major works. On 8 January 1970, he opened his second solo exhibition in Paris at the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 fran\u00e7aise de photographie]], ''Le soleil brilla toute la nuit'' (also known as ''...And the Sun Shone White All Night Long'' or ''...And the Sun It Shone White All Night Long'').<ref>{{cite news |title=John Max \u00e0 Paris |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2777762?docpos=10 |work=Le Devoir |date=9 January 1970|language=French}}</ref> 57 prints were exhibited, among Max\u2019s most expressive, in a highly charged and graphic style.<ref name=\"Lamothe\" />\n\nIn 1971, the TV documentary ''...to be INDIAN'' was broadcast by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC).<ref>{{cite news |title=Indian Philosophy Probed |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/481290057/ |work=[[Calgary Herald]] |date=26 March 1971}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref> Directed by [[Jesse Nishihata]], the movie was composed entirely of still photographs shot by Max, animated in the manner of NFB films such as ''[[City of Gold (1957 film)|City of Gold]]'', by [[Wolf Koenig]] and [[Colin Low (filmmaker)|Colin Low]] (a style that was later known as the \u201c[[Ken Burns Effect]]\u201d). The images were synchronized with interviews, and together they draw a portrait of three Indigenous communities in Alberta ([[University nuhelot\u02bc\u012fne thaiyots\u02bc\u012f nistameyim\u00e2kanak Blue Quills|Blue Quills College]], [[Frog Lake, Alberta|Frog Lake]], and [[Robert Smallboy#Smallboy Camp or Mountain Cree Camp|Smallboy Camp]]) during a tense moment in their relationships with the [[Canadian government]] about their [[Indian Register|Indian]] status, self-government, and revendications.<ref>{{cite web |title=The White Paper, 1969 |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/the-white-paper-1969 |website=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]}}</ref>\n\nFinally, in 1972 the exhibition ''Open Passport = Un passeport infini'' opened at the Photo Gallery of the NFB in [[Ottawa]].<ref name=\"NGC-OP\">{{cite web |title=Open Passport = Un passeport infini |url=http://library.gallery.ca/record=b1262304~S4 |website=Library and Archives \u2014 Catalogue |publisher=National Gallery of Canada}}</ref> A sequence of 161 black and white photographs culled from Max\u2019s archives, some dating as early as 1960, ''Open Passport'' is widely considered his most important work.<ref name=\"NGC-report\" /> The photographs are mainly portraits, of Max\u2019s family (his wife and son) and friends, many of which were established artists and personalities. Among those portrayed are [[Leonard Cohen]], [[Janis Joplin]], [[Sam Tata]], Fran\u00e7ois Dallegret, [[Vittorio Fiorucci]], Guy Borremans, Sylvain P. [Henri] Cousineau, [[Lorraine Monk]], [[Jean-Claude Germain]], [[Moondog]], [[Arthur Lipsett]], [[Frank Zappa]] and [[Gail Zappa]], Henry Zemel, Gordon Sheppard, [[Nina Raginsky]], [[Judith Eglington]], Charles Gagnon, [[Dennis Stock]], [[Martin Lavut]], [[Grace Slick]], and [[Michio Kushi]].<ref name=\"OP_BOOK\">{{cite book |last1=Max |first1=John |title=Open Pasport |date=1973 |publisher=IMPRESSIONS |location=Toronto |oclc=1118991051}}</ref>\n\nMax unified the selection for ''Open Passport'' by organizing the images according to a narrative progression, by grouping images in grids, using repetitions and a variety of sequencing strategies that can recall large-scale photographic exhibitions such as ''[[The Family of Man]]''. The underlying story is that of a couple confronting the arrival of a child: whilst the mother experiences an increasing toll on her sanity and her energy, the father confronts a dilemma between his artistic career and his family. The conflict is ultimately resolved by his departure, but this resolution is not considered a happy ending by those involved.<ref name=\"FakingDeath\">{{cite book |last1=Cousineau-Levine |first1=Penny |author1-link=Penny Cousineau-Levine |title=Faking Death: Canadian Art Photography and the Canadian Imagination |date=2003 |publisher=McGill-Queen\u2019s University Press |location=Montr\u00e9al and Kingston |isbn=0773525262 |url=https://www.mqup.ca/faking-death-products-9780773528260.php}}</ref><ref name=\"MHV-Uhl\">{{cite book |last1=Hardy-Vall\u00e9e |first1=Michel |editor1-last=Uhl |editor1-first=Magali |title=Les r\u00e9cits visuels de soi : Mises en r\u00e9cit artistiques et nouvelles sc\u00e9nographies de l\u2019intime |date=2015 |publisher=Presses universitaires de Paris ouest |language=French |location=Paris |isbn=9782840162285 |pages=197\u2013206 |url=https://presses.parisnanterre.fr/?p=2688 |chapter=Open Passport : Le r\u00e9cit photographique et le langage universel de John Max}}</ref>\n\n''Open Passport'' was accompanied by a slide show of the photographs at its opening in Ottawa and Montr\u00e9al,<ref name=\"White\">{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Michael |title=John Max: Photographs Born of a Beat Generation |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NIMuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qqEFAAAAIBAJ&hl=fr&pg=909%2C2693835 |work=The Gazette |date=10 February 1973}}</ref> and it traveled to multiple venues in Canada until 1976.<ref name=\"NGC-OP\" /> It was printed as a [[Photo-book|photobook]] by the [[Toronto]]-based magazine ''IMPRESSIONS'' as its special issue No. 6 and 7 in late 1973.<ref name=\"OP_BOOK\" /> [[A. D. Coleman|A.D. Coleman]] favourably reviewed it in the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Coleman|first1=A.D. |author1-link=A. D. Coleman|url=https://nyti.ms/1XVstnI|title=The Photography Book as Autobiography|date=11 August 1974|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=|url-status=live|page=D25}}{{subscription|s}}</ref>\n\n=== 1974\u20131995: Japan and back ===\n\nFollowing the critical success of ''Open Passport'', John Max was inducted to the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]] in 1974,<ref>{{cite web |title=Members - 1880 to the Present |url=http://www.rca-arc.ca/ |website=[[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]] |accessdate=4 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030201044301/http://www.rca-arc.ca/Members1880MtoN.htm |archivedate=1 February 2003}}</ref> and received a Senior Arts Grant from the [[Canada Council]] to travel to Japan to photograph.<ref>{{cite web |author1=[[Canada Council]] |title=1973\u201374 Annual Report |url=https://canadacouncil.ca/-/media/Files/CCA/Corporate/Annual-Reports/en/1973-74-Annual-Report.pdf |page=36}}</ref> He had long professed his interest in the country\u2019s culture and spirituality, and he stayed four years in the country, from 1974 to 1978. Unfortunately, he did not leave before the expiry of his visa, and he was arrested by the Japanese authorities, his thousands of rolls of film put in storage.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Purdie |first1=James |title=Rescue Urged for Max Film |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=11 November 1978 |ISSN=03190714}}</ref> Many of them were rendered unusable because of the storage conditions, but he eventually brought the remainder back in Canada.<ref name=\"Lamothe\" />\n\nDuring the 1980s, he did three solo exhibitions in small venues, which received limited press coverage: ''John Max: Images of Japan, 1974\u201379 Photographs'' (1982),<ref>{{cite news |last1=Daigneault |first1=Gilles |title=Les expositions / Il \u00e9tait une fois dans l\u2019est |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2769513?docpos=26 |work=Le Devoir |language=French|date=30 October 1982 |page=26}}</ref> ''On the Wings of a Mosquito: The Nothing and The Everything'' (1984) and ''Strike up the Band!'' (1986).<ref name=\"CV-MAX\">{{cite web |title=Curriculum Vitae, John Max |url=https://www.lacastiglione.ca/cv-john-max |website=La Castiglione }}</ref> In 1991 he was slated to present a career-spanning retrospective exhibition during the biennial [[Mois de la Photo \u00e0 Montr\u00e9al]], but he failed to the task, and delivered only two photographs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dumont |first1=Jean |title=Autres figurations |language=French |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2760934?docpos=12 |work=Le Devoir |date=28 September 1991 |page=12}}</ref> His photos were occasionally included in group exhibitions, and he showed some of his drawings in 1995.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cou\u00eblle |first1=Jennifer |title=Une affaire de tomates\u2026 |language=French |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2771399?docpos=10 |work=Le Devoir |date=19 October 1995 |page=B10}}</ref>\n\n=== 1997\u20132011: Rediscovery and final years ===\n\nIn the late 1990s, through the efforts of the Stephen Bulger Gallery in Toronto, and VOX in Montr\u00e9al, John Max exhibited photographs from ''Open Passport'', from Japan, and from ''On the Wings of a Mosquito'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Allaire |first1=Serge |title=John Max |journal=Ciel variable |date=Fall 1997 |volume=40 |language=French |url=http://cielvariable.ca/numeros/ciel-variable-40-releve-quebec-canada/john-max-serge-allaire/}}</ref> this time to greater critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lehman |first1=Henry |title=Echo is Heard from Career of a Talented Photographer |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/425049412 |work=The Gazette |date=5 April 1997}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref> The Mus\u00e9e de la Photographie \u00e0 [[Charleroi]], in [[Belgium]], showed his photographs and printed a catalogue, ''Quelque chose suit son cours = Something is taking its place'' (1998).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Max |first1=John |last2=Vercheval |first2=Georges |title=Quelque chose suit son cours = Something is Taking its Place |date=1998 |language=French,English |publisher=Mus\u00e9e de la photographie \u00e0 Charleroi |location=Charleroi, Belgium |isbn=9782871830306 |oclc=757584367}}</ref> Max was also part of the 1999 edition of the [[Noorderlicht]] Fotofestival in [[Groningen]], [[Netherlands]], and four photographs from ''Open Passport'' were printed in the catalogue, ''Wonderland''.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Melis |editor1-first=Wim |editor2-last=Botman |editor2-first=Machiel|title=Noorderlicht: Wonderland |date=1999 |publisher=Stichting Aurora Borealis |location=Groningen, Netherlands |isbn=9789076703039 |oclc=905439783}}</ref>\n\nDuring the early 2000s, his photos appeared in retrospective thematic group exhibitions of the [[Canadian Museum of Contemporary Photography]], the [[Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Montr\u00e9al|Mus\u00e9e d\u2019art contemporain de Montr\u00e9al]], and the [[Montr\u00e9al Museum of Fine Arts]].<ref name=\"CV-MAX\" /> Two projects concurrently attempted to sketch a biography of Max,\n{{ill|David Homel's|fr|David Homel}} [[essay]] ''Le monde est un document'' (2002), and [[Michel Lamothe]]\u2019s [[documentary film]] ''John Max: A Portrait'' (2010).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Homel |first1=David |last2=Homel |first2=David |title=Le monde est un document |date=2002 |publisher=\u00c9ditions J\u2019ai VU |location=Qu\u00e9bec City |isbn=9782922763041 |oclc=747175727 |language=French,English}}</ref><ref name=\"Lamothe\" /> Lamothe\u2019s movie was filmed around the time Max was being evicted from his house in 2003 and shows him in dire straits.\n\nThe sale of a complete set of exhibition prints of the original ''Open Passport'' exhibition to the Canadian Museum of Contemporary Photography afforded Max some financial security,<ref name=\"NGC-report\" /> while the support of his friends\u2014Lamothe, {{ill|Gabor Szilasi|fr}}, [[Claude Chamberland]] among others\u2014allowed the emptying of his overstuffed house and the safeguard of his photographic materials.<ref name=\"Block\" />\n\nHe lived in a Buddhist ashram for the final years of his life and died on 5 May 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nadeau |first1=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois |title=D\u00e9c\u00e8s du photographe John Max |language=French |url=http://numerique.banq.qc.ca/patrimoine/details/52327/2929895?docpos=9 |work=Le Devoir |date=7 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nJohn Max was married to medical illustrator Janet Peace (1933\u20132011). They had one son, David, to whom is dedicated ''Open Passport''.<ref name=\"OP_BOOK\" /> They divorced a few years following their marriage; Peace then lived in Mexico and Canada with her son and her second husband.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Loth |first1=Marlene |title=Janet Perez-Vela (obituray) |journal=BMCAAnewsletter |date=Spring 2012 |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=27\u20138 |publisher=Biomedical Communications Alumni Association |location=University of Toronto}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\nMany photographers and artists such as Benoit Aquin<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ewing |first1=William A. |title=Benoit Aquin: Fire & Ice = Benoit Aquin : De feu et de glace |journal=Ciel variable |date=2009 |pages=25\u201331 |url=https://id.erudit.org/iderudit/549ac|language=English,French}}</ref> and [[Marc S\u00e9guin]]<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Pichette |editor1-first=Jean |title=Marc S\u00e9guin : survol overview |date=2006 |publisher=[[Les 400 coups]] |location=Montr\u00e9al |isbn=9782895402091 |oclc=71186547|language=French,English}}</ref> have underlined the importance of John Max and of his works.\n\n''Open Passport'' has also been referenced by various works:\n* ''Mona Nima'' (1977) by Sylvain P. Cousineau.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cousineau |first1=Sylvain P. |title=Mona Nima |date=1977 |publisher=Powys Press |location=Almonte, ON |isbn=9780969062806 |url=https://www.cousineau.org/photographie#/mona-nima-xxxx/ |oclc=4048545}}</ref>\n* The artist book ''Hommage'' (2005) by Serge Cl\u00e9ment contains both a copy of ''Open Passport'' and Cl\u00e9ment\u2019s reinterpretation of it as an extended sequence.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cl\u00e9ment|first1=Serge|url=http://www.sergeclement.com/hommage-john-max-open-passport/|title=Hommage : John Max\u2014Open Passport|date=2005|publisher=S. Cl\u00e9ment|year=|isbn=|location=Montr\u00e9al|pages=|oclc=62430203}}</ref>\n* Composer [[Christopher Mayo]] has released ''To Discard all Images'' (2019), a piece for voice and instruments combining recordings of the reactions of photographers to ''Open Passport'' with Mayo\u2019s original score.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mayo |first1=Christopher |author1-link=Christopher Mayo|title=To Discard All Images |url=https://soundcloud.com/christophermayo/to-discard-all-images}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Exhibitions ===\nSince many of the following exhibitions also [[Travelling exhibition|traveled]] to a multiplicity of sites over many years, only the opening place and year are indicated.\n\n==== Solo ====\n* '''1960''' ''John Max Shouts: Enough, No More, I Want'', McGill University, Montr\u00e9al\n* '''1970''' ''Le soleil brilla toute la nuit = And the Sun It Shone White All Night Long'', Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Fran\u00e7aise de Photographie, Paris\n* '''1972''' ''Open Passport = Un passeport infini'', The NFB Photo Gallery, Ottawa\n* '''1982''' ''John Max: Images of Japan, 1974\u201379 Photographs'', A.R. Encadrements, Montr\u00e9al\n* '''1984''' ''On the Wings of a Mosquito: The Nothing and The Everything'', Dazibao, Montr\u00e9al\n* '''1986''' ''Strike up the Band!'', The Art Workshop, Montr\u00e9al\n* '''1997''' ''Swallowing a Diamond'', Stephen Bulger Gallery, Toronto\n* '''1997''' ''Open Passport'', VOX, Montr\u00e9al\n\n==== Selected group exhibitions ====\n* '''1957''' Photographie 57, Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al\n* '''1963''' Photography 63 / An International Exhibition, George Eastman House\n* '''1967''' 5<sup>e</sup> Biennale de Paris, [[Mus\u00e9e d'Art Moderne de Paris|Mus\u00e9e d'art moderne de Paris]]\n* '''1967''' Universal and International Exhibition, Montreal Expo \u201967\n* '''1967''' Bytown International Photographic Exhibition, Camera Club of Ottawa<ref>{{cite book |title=Bytown International 1967 Exposition photographique Canada |date=1967 |publisher=Camera Club of Ottawa|oclc=80536898|language=English,French}}</ref>\n* '''1967''' Photography in Canada 1967 = Photographie au Canada 1967, NFB\n* '''1968''' Other Places = Sous d\u2019autres cieux, NFB\n* '''1969''' Seeds of the spacefields = Cela commen\u00e7a par un r\u00eave et ce fut la cr\u00e9ation, NFB\n* '''1969''' Image 6: Photography in Canada 1969 = Photographie au Canada 1969, NFB\n* '''1969''' Quatre photographes montr\u00e9alais: Marc-Andr\u00e9 Gagn\u00e9, Ronald Labelle, John Max, Michel Saint-Jean = Four Montreal Photographers, National Gallery of Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Four Montreal photographers |url=http://library.gallery.ca/record=b1125748~S4 |website=National Gallery of Canada}}</ref>\n* '''1999''' Wonderland, Noorderlicht Photofestival\n\n=== Publications ===\n\n==== Monographs ====\n{{refbegin|indent=yes}}\n* '''1973''' {{cite book |last1=Max |first1=John |title=Open Pasport  |publisher=IMPRESSIONS |location=Toronto |oclc=1118991051}}\n* '''1998''' {{cite book |last1=Max |first1=John |last2=Vercheval |first2=Georges |title=Quelque chose suit son cours = Something is Taking its Place |publisher=Mus\u00e9e de la photographie \u00e0 Charleroi |location=Charleroi, Belgium |isbn=9782871830306 |oclc=757584367|language=French,English}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==== Collective works ====\n{{refbegin|indent=yes|}}\n* '''1957''' {{cite book|last1=Millet|first1=Robert|title=quelques uns des travaux expos\u00e9s d\u2019abord \u00e0 l\u2019Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al en f\u00e9vrier \u201957 par un groupe qui croit que la photographie est autre chose qu\u2019un m\u00e9dium impersonnel de reproduction\u2026|oclc=938043393|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Artistique de l\u2019Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al|year=|isbn=|location=Montr\u00e9al|language=French|pages=}}\n* '''1963''' {{cite book|last=|first=|title=Photography 63 / An International Exhibition|publisher=George Eastman House|year=|isbn=|location=Rochester, NY|pages=|oclc=613432467}}\n* '''1968''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor-last1=Monk|editor-first1=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Call them Canadians: A Photographic Point of View|publisher=Queen\u2019s Printer|year=|location=Ottawa|pages=|oclc=622822727}}\n* '''1968''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor-last1=Monk|editor-first1=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Ces visages qui sont un pays|publisher=Imprimeur de la Reine|year=|location=Ottawa|pages=|language=French|oclc=604354983}}\n* '''1968''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor1-last=Monk|editor1-first=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Photography = Photographie Canada 1967|publisher=National Film Board of Canada|year=|location=Ottawa|pages=|oclc=191407|series=IMAGE vol. 2|language=English,French}}\n* '''1968''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor1-last=Monk|editor1-first=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Other Places = Sous d\u2019autres cieux|publisher=National Film Board of Canada|year=|location=Ottawa|pages=|oclc=30071341|series=IMAGE vol. 3|language=English,French}}\n* '''1969''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor1-last=Monk|editor1-first=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Seeds of the spacefields (a sequence of ten dreams) = cela commen\u00e7a par un r\u00eave et ce fut la Cr\u00e9ation (une s\u00e9rie de dix r\u00eaves)|publisher=Martlet Press|year=|location=Toronto|pages=|oclc=62931108|series=IMAGE vol. 5|language=English,French}}\n* '''1970''' {{cite book|isbn=|editor1-last=Monk|editor1-first=Lorraine|last=|first=|title=Image 6: A Review of Contemporary Photography in Canada = Une revue de la photographie contemporaine au Canada|publisher=Martlet Press|year=|location=Toronto|pages=|oclc=1131342409|series=IMAGE vol. 6|language=English,French}}\n* '''1999''' {{cite book|editor1-last=Melis|editor1-first=Wim|editor2-last=Botman|editor2-first=Machiel|last=|first=|title=Noorderlicht: Wonderland|publisher=Stichting Aurora Borealis|location=Groningen, Netherlands|pages=|year=|isbn=9789076703039|oclc=905439783}}\n* '''2002''' {{cite book|editor1-last=Pichette|editor1-first=Jean|last=|first=|title=Les tours de Babel : La paix apr\u00e8s le 11 septembre|publisher=Les 400 coups|location=Montr\u00e9al|pages=|year=|language=French|isbn=9782895400813|oclc=61445224|series=Sortir la t\u00eate}}\n* '''2002''' {{cite book|last1=Homel|first1=David|last2=Homel|