eastman.org/people/40405/john-max |website=George Eastman Museum}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://rca-arc.ca/who-we-are/members/members-since-1880/ List of members, Royal Canadian Academy of the Arts]\n* [https://www.gallery.ca/collection/artist/john-max National Gallery of Canada]\n* [https://www.bulgergallery.com/ Stephen Bulger Gallery]\n* [http://www.centrevox.ca/fd/artiste_select.php?artiste=66 VOX, Centre de l'image contemporaine]\n* [https://www.lacastiglione.ca/john-max Galerie La Castiglione]\n\n{{Authority control |VIAF=52934352 |LCCN=n/77/006662 |ISNI=0000 0001 1763 5828 |GND=174341776 |WORLDCATID=lccn-n77006662}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Max, John}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian photographers]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Quebec people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Artists from Quebec]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian photographers]]\n[[Category:Canadian photojournalists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]]\n[[Category:National Film Board of Canada people]]\n[[Category:Photography in Canada]]\n[[Category:Photography in Japan]]\n[[Category:Street photographers]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian diaspora in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMarc S\u00e9guin(link changed toMarc S\u00e9guin (painter)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Max"}
{"title_page": "Trade Union International of Workers in the Metal Industry", "text_new": "The '''Trade Union International of Workers in the Metal Industry''' was a [[trade union international]] affiliated to the [[World Federation of Trade Unions]].\n\n== History ==\nThe TUI was founded at a conference in [[Turin]], [[Italy]] on June 2, 1949 as the Trade Union International of the Metal and Engineering Industries.<ref>[[A. Percy Coldrick|Coldrick, A. Percy]] and [[Philip James Jones|Jones, Philip]]. ''The international directory of the trade union movement'' New York : Facts on File, [1978] pp.191-2</ref> (Other sources say June 21.)<ref>''[https://archive.org/details/dudeman5685_yahoo_WFTU The World Federation of Trade Unions, 1945-1985. ]'' Prague; Published by the WTFU in cooperation with PRACE Czechoslovak Trade Unions 1985 p.153</ref>\n\nIn 1998 the TUI merged with the [[Trade Unions International of Chemical, Oil and Allied Workers]] and the [[Trade Unions International of Miners|Trade Union International of Energy Workers]] to found the Trade Union International of Energy, Metal, Chemical, Oil and Allied Industries at a conference in [[Havana]]. In 2007 the latter reformed as the [[Trade Union International of Energy Workers (2007)|Trade Union International of Energy Workers]]. The metal and mining workers then formed the [[Trade Union International of Workers in the Mining, the Metallurgy and the Metal Industries]].<ref>''[[Europa World Year Book]]'' London; Taylor & Francis, 2004 p.342</ref><ref>World Federation of Trade Unions ''[http://www.wftucentral.org/download/documents/documents%20en/WFTU_REPORT%20OF%20ACTION_2006-2010_EN.pdf Report of Action 2006-2010]'' p.104</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\nThe highest organ of the TUI was the International Trade Conference held every four years which elected an administrative committee and a secretariat.<ref>Coldrick and Jones p.191</ref> It also had specialized commissions on [[Steel industry|steel]], [[shipbuilding]], the [[automobile industry]], mechanical and electro-electronic constr4uction as well as a Standing Committee on Peace and Disarmament.<ref>''The World Federation of Trade Unions, 1945-1985'' p.154</ref>\n\nIn 1955 its address was reported as [[Seilerstaette]] 3, [[Vienna]] [[Innere Stadt|1]], [[Austria]]. It shared the address with the [[Trade Unions International of Miners Unions]], the [[Trade Unions International of Transport Workers]] and the [[World Federation of Teachers Unions]].<ref>''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/100074996 Directory of World Federation of Trade Unions]'' Washington [[Office of International Labor Affairs]], June 1955 pp.47-8</ref> By 1957 its headquarters were Janska 100, [[Prague]] [[Prague 1|1]], [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Czechoslovakia]] where it again shared the address with the TUIs of Transport Workers, Miners and Teachers<ref>''[https://archive.org/details/frontorgs Facts about international Communist front organisations]'' p. 55</ref><ref>''Directory of World Federation of Trade Union'' 1958 pp.53-6</ref> By 1978 it moved to BP158 [[Moscow]] K9, [[Soviet Union]],<ref>Coldrick and Jones p.192</ref> an address it would keep until at least 1991.<ref>[[Martin Upham|Upham, Martin]] ''Trade unions of the world, 1992-1993.'' Harlow, Essex, U.K. : Longman ; Detroit, Mich. : Distributed exclusively in the U.S. and Canada by Gale Research Inc.,  1991 p.558</ref>\n\n== Members ==\nAt the TUIs founding conference in 1949 there 62 delegates representing 16 countries and seven and half million workers. Five other countries were represented by observers. States represented included the Soviet Union, Czechoslovakia, Italy, [[France]] and the [[Netherlands]].<ref>Coldrick and Jones p.191</ref> In 1958 it claimed 10,050,000 members in 18 countries.<ref>''Directory of World Federation of Trade Union'' 1958 p.53</ref> In 1976 the TUI included 36 organizations in 28 countries representing 20 million members.<ref>Coldrick and Jones p.191</ref> And in 1985 it claimed 58 affiliates in 42 countries representing 22 million workers.<ref>''The World Federation of Trade Unions, 1945-1985'' pp.153-4</ref>\n\n*{{flag|Austria}} - [[Fraktion Gewerkschaftlicher Linksblock in der Gewerkschaft der Metal und Bergarbeiter]]\n*{{flag|Benin|1975}} - [[Syndicat Professionnel des Travaileurs de la Mechanique Generale et de la Metalurgie]]\n*{{flag|Bulgaria|1967}} -  [[Union of Workers in Engineering Industry]]\n*{{flag|Chile}} - [[Co-operation Exteriure]] de [[Confederaci\u00f3n Unitaria de Trabajadores (Chile)|CUT]]\n*{{flag|Cyprus}} - [[Cyprus Mechanics and Electricians Trade Unions]]\n*{{flag|Colombia}} - [[Federaci\u00f3n Nacional de Trabajadores del Metal]]\n*{{flag|Congo|1970}} - [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Syndicale des Travaileurs de l'Industrie et de la Metalurgie]]\n*{{flag|Cuba}} - [[Federaci\u00f3n Nacional de Trabajadores de Industria Basica]]\n*{{flag|Czechoslovakia}} - [[Union of Workers in the Metal Industries]]\n*{{flag|El Salvador}} - [[Sindicato de Trabajadores de la Industria Mecanica y Metalicas Basica]]\n*{{flag|France}} - [[Metalworkers' Federation]], [[CGT (France)|CGT]]\n*{{flag|France}} - [[National Federation of State Workers]]\n*{{flag|East Germany}} - [[Industriegewerkschaft Metall]]\n*{{flag|Hungary|1957}} - [[National Federation of Metal Workers]]\n*{{flag|India}} - [[National Federation of Metal and Engineering Workers of India]]\n*{{flag|India}} - [[All India Steel Workers' Federation]]\n*{{flag|Iraq|1963}} - [[General Trade Union of Metalworkers]]\n*{{flag|Jordan}} - [[General Federation of Jordanian Trade Unions]], [[General Federation of Metal Workers]]\n*{{flag|North Korea}} - [[Union of Metal and Engineering Workers of Korea]]\n*{{flag|Madagascar}} - [[Syndicat des Travailleurs des la Metalurgie, Bois et Batiments]] [[Fi.Se.Ma.]]\n*{{flag|Nigeria}} - [[Nigerian Steel Development Authority Workers' Union]]\n*{{flag|Peru}} - [[Federaci\u00f3n de Trabajadores de la Industria del Metal de Peru]], [[CGTP (Peru)|CGTP]]\n*{{flag|Poland}} - [[Zwi\u0105zek Zawodowy Hutnik\u00f3w w Polsce]]\n*{{flag|Poland}} - [[Zwi\u0105zek Zawodowy Metalowc\u00f3w w Polsce]]\n*{{flag|Romania|1965}} - [[Union des Syndicats des enterprises de l'Industrie Metallurgique et de Constructions Mechanique]]\n*{{flag|Soviet Union}} - [[Central Committee of the Metalworkers Union]]\n*{{flag|Soviet Union}} - [[Central Committee of the Engineering Workers Union]]\n*{{flag|Soviet Union}} - [[Central Committee of the Power-station Workers Union]]\n*{{flag|Soviet Union}} - [[Central Committee of the Shipbuilding Workers Union]]\n*{{flag|Sri Lanka}} - [[Industrial and General Workers Union]]\n*{{flag|Sri Lanka}} - [[Ceylon Engineering Workers Union]]\n*{{flag|Syria}} - [[Professional Federation of Mining, Light Industry and Mechanical Workers]]\n*{{flag|Uruguay}} - [[Uni\u00f3n Nacional de Trabajadores del Metal y Rames Afines]]\n*{{flag|Venezuela}} - [[SINATRAMETAL]]\n*{{flag|Venezuela}} - [[Sindicato Unificado de Trabajadores de la Siderugia, de las Minas, del Metal, del Automovil y de la ramas afines]]\n*{{flag|Vietnam}} - [[National Union of Metal and Engineering Workers]]\n\n==General Secretaries==\n:1952: Henri Jourdain\n:1957: Giacomo Adduci\n:1964: [[Pierre Gensous]]\n:1966: [[Jean Desmaison]]\n:1969: Mauro Pacci\n:1980s: Alain Stern\n:1987: Daniel Bailly\n:c.1990: Gilbert Le Bescond\n\n== See also ==\n*[[International Metalworkers' Federation]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Trade unions established in 1949]]\n[[Category:1949 establishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:Trade Unions Internationals]]\n[[Category:Trade unions disestablished in 1997]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Metal trade unions]]\n[[Category:Defunct transnational trade unions]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Trade Union International of Workers in the Metal Industry''' was a [[trade union international]] affiliated to the [[World Federation of Trade Unions]].\n\n== History ==\nThe TUI was founded at a conference in [[Turin]], [[Italy]] on June 2, 1949 as the Trade Union International of the Metal and Engineering Industries.<ref>[[A. Percy Coldrick|Coldrick, A. Percy]] and [[Philip James Jones|Jones, Philip]]. ''The international directory of the trade union movement'' New York : Facts on File, [1978] pp.191-2</ref> (Other sources say June 21.)<ref>''[https://archive.org/details/dudeman5685_yahoo_WFTU The World Federation of Trade Unions, 1945-1985. ]'' Prague; Published by the WTFU in cooperation with PRACE Czechoslovak Trade Unions 1985 p.153</ref>\n\nIn 1998 the TUI merged with the [[Trade Unions International of Chemical, Oil and Allied Workers]] and the [[Trade Unions International of Miners|Trade Union International of Energy Workers]] to found the Trade Union International of Energy, Metal, Chemical, Oil and Allied Industries at a conference in [[Havana]]. In 2007 the latter reformed as the [[Trade Union International of Energy Workers (2007)|Trade Union International of Energy Workers]]. The metal and mining workers then formed the [[Trade Union International of Workers in the Mining, the Metallurgy and the Metal Industries]].<ref>''[[Europa World Year Book]]'' London; Taylor & Francis, 2004 p.342</ref><ref>World Federation of Trade Unions ''[http://www.wftucentral.org/download/documents/documents%20en/WFTU_REPORT%20OF%20ACTION_2006-2010_EN.pdf Report of Action 2006-2010]'' p.104</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\nThe highest organ of the TUI was the International Trade Conference held every four years which elected an administrative committee and a secretariat.<ref>Coldrick and Jones p.191</ref> It also had specialized commissions on [[Steel industry|steel]], [[shipbuilding]], the [[automobile industry]], mechanical and electro-electronic constr4uction as well as a Standing Committee on Peace and Disarmament.<ref>''The World Federation of Trade Unions, 1945-1985'' p.154</ref>\n\nIn 1955 its address was reported as [[Seilerstaette]] 3, [[Vienna]] [[Innere Stadt|1]], [[Austria]]. It shared the address with the [[Trade Unions International of Miners Unions]], the [[Trade Unions International of Transport Workers]] and the [[World Federation of Teachers Unions]].<ref>''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/100074996 Directory of World Federation of Trade Unions]'' Washington [[Office of International Labor Affairs]], June 1955 pp.47-8</ref> By 1957 its headquarters were Janska 100, [[Prague]] [[Prague 1|1]], [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Czechoslovakia]] where it again shared the address with the TUIs of Transport Workers, Miners and Teachers<ref>''[https://archive.org/details/frontorgs Facts about international Communist front organisations]'' p. 55</ref><ref>''Directory of World Federation of Trade Union'' 1958 pp.53-6</ref> By 1978 it moved to BP158 [[Moscow]] K9, [[Soviet Union]],<ref>Coldrick and Jones p.192</ref> an address it would keep until at least 1991.<ref>[[Martin Upham|Upham, Martin]] ''Trade unions of the world, 1992-1993.'' Harlow, Essex, U.K. : Longman ; Detroit, Mich. : Distributed exclusively in the U.S. and Canada by Gale Research Inc.,  1991 p.558</ref>\n\n== Members ==\nAt the TUIs founding conference in 1949 there 62 delegates representing 16 countries and seven and half million workers. Five other countries were represented by observers. States represented included the Soviet Union, Czechoslovakia, Italy, [[France]] and the [[Netherlands]].<ref>Coldrick and Jones p.191</ref> In 1958 it claimed 10,050,000 members in 18 countries.<ref>''Directory of World Federation of Trade Union'' 1958 p.53</ref> In 1976 the TUI included 36 organizations in 28 countries representing 20 million members.<ref>Coldrick and Jones p.191</ref> And in 1985 it claimed 58 affiliates in 42 countries representing 22 million workers.<ref>''The World Federation of Trade Unions, 1945-1985'' pp.153-4</ref>\n\n*{{flag|Austria}} - [[Fraktion Gewerkschaftlicher Linksblock in der Gewerkschaft der Metal und Bergarbeiter]]\n*{{flag|Benin|1975}} - [[Syndicat Professionnel des Travaileurs de la Mechanique Generale et de la Metalurgie]]\n*{{flag|Bulgaria|1967}} -  [[Union of Workers in Engineering Industry]]\n*{{flag|Chile}} - [[Co-operation Exteriure]] de [[Confederaci\u00f3n Unitaria de Trabajadores (Chile)|CUT]]\n*{{flag|Cyprus}} - [[Cyprus Mechanics and Electricians Trade Unions]]\n*{{flag|Colombia}} - [[Federaci\u00f3n Nacional de Trabajadores del Metal]]\n*{{flag|Congo|1970}} - [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Syndicale des Travaileurs de l'Industrie et de la Metalurgie]]\n*{{flag|Cuba}} - [[Federaci\u00f3n Nacional de Trabajadores de Industria Basica]]\n*{{flag|Czechoslovakia}} - [[Union of Workers in the Metal Industries]]\n*{{flag|El Salvador}} - [[Sindicato de Trabajadores de la Industria Mecanica y Metalicas Basica]]\n*{{flag|France}} - [[Metalworkers' Federation]], [[CGT (France)|CGT]]\n*{{flag|France}} - [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Nationale des Travailleurs de l'Etat]]\n*{{flag|East Germany}} - [[Industriegewerkschaft Metall]]\n*{{flag|Hungary|1957}} - [[National Federation of Metal Workers]]\n*{{flag|India}} - [[National Federation of Metal and Engineering Workers of India]]\n*{{flag|India}} - [[All India Steel Workers' Federation]]\n*{{flag|Iraq|1963}} - [[General Trade Union of Metalworkers]]\n*{{flag|Jordan}} - [[General Federation of Jordanian Trade Unions]], [[General Federation of Metal Workers]]\n*{{flag|North Korea}} - [[Union of Metal and Engineering Workers of Korea]]\n*{{flag|Madagascar}} - [[Syndicat des Travailleurs des la Metalurgie, Bois et Batiments]] [[Fi.Se.Ma.]]\n*{{flag|Nigeria}} - [[Nigerian Steel Development Authority Workers' Union]]\n*{{flag|Peru}} - [[Federaci\u00f3n de Trabajadores de la Industria del Metal de Peru]], [[CGTP (Peru)|CGTP]]\n*{{flag|Poland}} - [[Zwi\u0105zek Zawodowy Hutnik\u00f3w w Polsce]]\n*{{flag|Poland}} - [[Zwi\u0105zek Zawodowy Metalowc\u00f3w w Polsce]]\n*{{flag|Romania|1965}} - [[Union des Syndicats des enterprises de l'Industrie Metallurgique et de Constructions Mechanique]]\n*{{flag|Soviet Union}} - [[Central Committee of the Metalworkers Union]]\n*{{flag|Soviet Union}} - [[Central Committee of the Engineering Workers Union]]\n*{{flag|Soviet Union}} - [[Central Committee of the Power-station Workers Union]]\n*{{flag|Soviet Union}} - [[Central Committee of the Shipbuilding Workers Union]]\n*{{flag|Sri Lanka}} - [[Industrial and General Workers Union]]\n*{{flag|Sri Lanka}} - [[Ceylon Engineering Workers Union]]\n*{{flag|Syria}} - [[Professional Federation of Mining, Light Industry and Mechanical Workers]]\n*{{flag|Uruguay}} - [[Uni\u00f3n Nacional de Trabajadores del Metal y Rames Afines]]\n*{{flag|Venezuela}} - [[SINATRAMETAL]]\n*{{flag|Venezuela}} - [[Sindicato Unificado de Trabajadores de la Siderugia, de las Minas, del Metal, del Automovil y de la ramas afines]]\n*{{flag|Vietnam}} - [[National Union of Metal and Engineering Workers]]\n\n==General Secretaries==\n:1952: Henri Jourdain\n:1957: Giacomo Adduci\n:1964: [[Pierre Gensous]]\n:1966: [[Jean Desmaison]]\n:1969: Mauro Pacci\n:1980s: Alain Stern\n:1987: Daniel Bailly\n:c.1990: Gilbert Le Bescond\n\n== See also ==\n*[[International Metalworkers' Federation]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Trade unions established in 1949]]\n[[Category:1949 establishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:Trade Unions Internationals]]\n[[Category:Trade unions disestablished in 1997]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Metal trade unions]]\n[[Category:Defunct transnational trade unions]]\n", "name_user": "Warofdreams", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trade_Union_International_of_Workers_in_the_Metal_Industry"}
